Dr. Francis Collins, a prominent scientist, has had an illustrious career at the National Institutes of Health (NIH) where he contributed to the sequencing and mapping of the human genome. He received recognition for his work, including the Presidential Medal of Freedom. He played a key role in advancing precision medicine and leading initiatives to understand neurological diseases and find a cure for cancer. Dr. Collins was asked to continue leading the NIH during the COVID-19 pandemic and was instrumental in the development of the COVID-19 vaccine. President Biden asked him to stay on to help establish the Advanced Research Project Agency for Health (ARPA-H). Dr. Collins has decided to step down from his position at the end of the year, leaving behind a lasting impact on millions of lives.